            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1327377955,
            "creation_date": 1327377214,
            "body": "<p>You can load any resource that is available on the classpath, which your jar would be a part of, using <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/ClassLoader.html#getResource%28java.lang.String%29\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>ClassLoader.getResource(String)<\/code><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>You can obtain a reference to a relevant <code>ClassLoader<\/code> object using <code>Class.getClassLoader()<\/code><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>ClassLoader cl = MyClass.class.getClassLoader();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If your image were named <code>myimage.png<\/code> and in a directory called <code>images<\/code> inside your jar, you could get the image like so.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>URL url = cl.getResource(\"images/myimage.png\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You can then use the URL to create an image object in memory.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Image i = Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit().createImage(url);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981805,
            "question_id": 8981783,
            "last_edit_date": 1327377955
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/03e5424d483e6c43736a81927ab7b81c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 121984,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 315483,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/315483/milind-ganjoo",
                "reputation": 1280,
                "display_name": "Milind Ganjoo",
                "accept_rate": 86
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1327377465,
            "creation_date": 1327377465,
            "body": "<p>The tutorial on <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/components/icon.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">How to Use Icons<\/a> at the Java website may be of use to  you.<\/p>\n\n<p>You'll do something like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>java.net.URL imgURL = this.getClass().getResource(path);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The <code>getResource()<\/code> method uses the same loading rules as defined by the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/ClassLoader.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>ClassLoader<\/code><\/a> for the class.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981832,
            "question_id": 8981783
        }
